    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Product = pair with projections fst and snd.
; The factorizer builds the unique morphism m.

(define (fst p) (car p))
(define (snd p) (cadr p))

; factorizer: given any two functions p: c->a and q: c->b,
; produce the unique m: c -> (a, b)
(define (factorizer p q)
  (lambda (x) (list (p x) (q x))))

; Example: c = integer, a = bool (is-even?), b = string (show)
(define (is-even? n) (= 0 (modulo n 2)))
(define (show n) (number->string n))

(define m (factorizer is-even? show))

(display "m(42):  ") (display (m 42)) (newline)
(display "m(7):   ") (display (m 7)) (newline)

; Verify: fst . m = is-even?, snd . m = show
(display "fst(m(42)) = is-even?(42)? ")
(display (equal? (fst (m 42)) (is-even? 42))) (newline)
(display "snd(m(42)) = show(42)?     ")
(display (equal? (snd (m 42)) (show 42)))
; The factorizer witnesses the universal property.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Product = tuple with fst, snd projections
fst = lambda p: p[0]
snd = lambda p: p[1]

# Factorizer: given p: c->a and q: c->b, build m: c->(a,b)
def factorizer(p, q):
    return lambda x: (p(x), q(x))

is_even = lambda n: n % 2 == 0
show = str

m = factorizer(is_even, show)
print(f"m(42) = {m(42)}")
print(f"m(7)  = {m(7)}")

# Verify universal property
print(f"fst(m(42)) == is_even(42)? {fst(m(42)) == is_even(42)}")
print(f"snd(m(42)) == show(42)?    {snd(m(42)) == show(42)}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Coproducts -->
    <h3>Coproducts — tagged unions from injections</h3>
    <p>Reverse the arrows and you get the <strong>coproduct</strong>. Instead of projections <em>out</em>, you have injections <em>in</em>: <code>Left : a → c</code> and <code>Right : b → c</code>. The universal property: for any other candidate <em>c'</em> with injections <em>i'</em> and <em>j'</em>, there exists a unique morphism <code>m : c → c'</code> where <code>i' = m ∘ Left</code> and <code>j' = m ∘ Right</code>. In programming, the coproduct is <code>Either</code> (Haskell) or a tagged union.</p>

